  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jdg 3:6-7",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 3:6-7",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They took their daughters, and served their gods — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Were drawn to idolatry by the persuasions and examples of their yoke-fellows. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And served Baalim and the groves — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Baalim in groves; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that is, false gods, or rather their images, set up under shady trees, contrary to the command given ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Some expositors, however, think the meaning is, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Baalim and Ashtaroth; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for by the addition of a single letter, the Hebrew word rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "groves, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "will be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ashtaroth, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and the greater part of the versions so render it, understanding thereby ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "goddesses, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "as distinguished from Baalim or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "lords. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It must be acknowledged, however, that the trees themselves, which composed those shady retreats in which they placed their idols, and which were consecrated to their honour, were accounted sacred by the ancient pagans, and held in great veneration. They decorated them with ribands and lights, made vows to them, and hung the spoils of their enemies upon them: insomuch that it was customary for travellers to stop, when they were to pass by them, and approach them with veneration and religious awe, as if they had been the habitation of some god.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3:1-7 As the Israelites were a type of the church on earth, they were not to be idle and slothful. The Lord was pleased to try them by the remains of the devoted nations they spared. Temptations and trials detect the wickedness of the hearts of sinners; and strengthen he graces of believers in their daily conflict with Satan, sin, and this evil world. They must live in this world, but they are not of it, and are forbidden to conform to it. This marks the difference between the followers of Christ and mere professors. The friendship of the world is more fatal than its enmity; the latter can only kill the body, but the former murders many precious souls.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
