  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 6.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They took their daughters",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. Here is a further downward step in the disobedience of the Israelites. Intermarriage with the Canaanite nations had been expressly forbidden (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 34:15, 16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 23:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the reason of the prohibition clearly stated, and for some time after Joshua's death no such marriages appear to have been contracted. But now the fatal step was taken, and the predicted consequence immediately ensued: \"they served their gods;.., they forgat the Lord their God, and served the Baalim and the Asheroth.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " CHAPTER 3:7-11 This section introduces us into the actual narrative of the Book of Judges, the prefatory matter being now concluded. The whole book proceeds on the same model as this section does. The apostasy of Israel; their servitude under the oppressor sent to chastise them; their cry of distress and penitence; their deliverance by the judge raised up to save them; the rest which follows their deliverance. There is infinite variety in the details of the successive narratives, but they are all formed on the same plan. Judges 3:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
